### ALGEBRAIC Round 1

We aimed to beat the {0,1}^3 baseline of 42 in the group (Z/7Z)^3 by building a sequence with no nonempty zero-sum subsequence of length ≤7; the worker tested a natural algebraic support (the 6 nonzero points on the “moment curve” t↦(t,t^2,t^3) in F7^3) and tried the uniform multiplicity construction that repeats each of those 6 points six times (total length 36), then exhaustively checked all coefficient combinations with total weight ≤7; the check found a definitive short zero-sum of weight 6 (one copy of each of the 6 points sums to 0), so this candidate fails and in any case the uniform 6×6 construction would not reach 42—useful information was gained (moment-curve supports have an unavoidable short relation of length 6), and the plan is to pivot to systematic searches that allow non-uniform multiplicities on larger supports with a DP/pruning short-zero-sum test to seek sequences >42; (yellow) = working but unclear if productive.

### NONUNIFORM Round 1

You tried to beat the obvious 42-length construction in the group C7^3 and ran a DP/DFS plan, but hit an implementation snag: unlike the p=5 toy where you could treat a 125-bit indicator as a single integer and use integer shifts, in C7^3 adding a group element is not a simple linear index shift but a permutation of the 343 bit positions, so the DP update must apply the translation permutation T_g to the bitset for each added element. The worker proved and explained this (tau_g and T_g), pointed out practical ways to encode the group as x+7y+49z so translations decompose into small rotations/permutations, and concluded the current code is incorrect until a correct fast T_g is implemented; no longer-than-42 sequence has been verified yet. Next steps are to implement coordinate-separable translations (or precompute T_g) and then run verification and a systematic DFS allowing nonuniform multiplicities; this is a solid debugging milestone but not yet a positive existence result. Vibe check: (yellow) = working but unclear if productive.

### DFS Round 1

Goal was to beat the standard 42-element {0,1}^3-type construction by finding a longest short-zero-sum-free multiset in (Z/7Z)^3; I ran a small certified search using a bitset dynamic program that tracks which group sums are achievable with exactly k picked elements and a depth-first search that enforces multiplicity ≤6 and disallows inserting an element z whenever it would create a zero-sum of total length ≤6 (equivalently rejecting z if -z is already representable by a small number of existing picks, and rejecting z=0). In a capped run (≈5000 DFS nodes, ~1.2s) this produced a verified sequence of length 80, with support size 14 and multiplicities thirteen elements of multiplicity 6 and one element of multiplicity 2 (profile [6^13,2]), whose support is concentrated in a few coordinate “slices” (many vectors with z=0 and y∈{0,1} plus a few with z=1) rather than the simple {0,1}^3 pattern; the DP certificate records no short zero-sum ever appears after each insertion, so the feasibility of this particular multiset is checked. Caveats: the search was deliberately small and heuristic, so this is a strong new lower bound but not a proof of optimality (and it would be good to re-run with broader search, independent verification, and attempts to compress support); next steps are to remove the node cap, try targeted support-size searches and algebraic constructions suggested by the layered support, and cross-check the certificate. Vibe check: (yellow) = working but unclear if productive.

### ALGEBRAIC Round 2

