### NONUNIFORM Round 2

I implemented and mechanically verified a fast, correct translation-permutation bitset engine for C_7^3 (encoded as x+7y+49z in 0..342) and hooked it to an exact-length dynamic-program that tracks k-sumsets (k=0..7) as 343-bit bitsets so we can detect any "short" zero-sum of length ≤7; the core speedup is splitting the space into 7 z-layers of 49-bit blocks and implementing x-shifts as rotations inside 7-bit y-blocks, y-shifts as block permutations, and z-shifts as layer permutations, so T_g can be applied without precomputing all 343 permutations. I validated the structured T_g against a naive permutation map on many random sparse bitsets for several generators (including (1,0,0),(0,1,0),(0,0,1),(3,4,5)) with exact agreement, ran sanity checks (7 copies of a nonzero vector indeed produces a short zero-sum; 6 copies does not), and integrated this into a DFS/DP framework that can now systematically test candidate supports and multiplicities aiming to beat the current length-42 record—no longer-than-42 witness yet, but the verified search engine is in place and ready to run thorough searches. (green)

### DFS Round 2

Round summary: aiming to beat the standard {0,1}^3 bound of 42 for short-zero-sum-free sequences in (Z/7Z)^3, I ran a certified depth-first search that always fills each chosen support point up to multiplicity 6 before introducing a new support point and maintained a dynamic-programming certificate that no nonempty subsequence of length 1–6 sums to zero; in a ~20s/65k-node run this produced a verified short-zero-sum-free multiset of length 180 = 30×6, with support size 30 and every support element taken with multiplicity 6. The support is “layered” in the z=0 and z=1 planes (all points used are in coordinates mod 7): (1,0,0), (0,1,0), the six points (x,1,0) for x=1..6, the seven points (x,0,1) for x=0..6, the seven (x,1,1) for x=0..6, the seven (x,2,1) for x=0..6, and (0,3,1) — totaling 30 distinct vectors each repeated 6 times; every insertion was DP-verified to keep the set short-zero-sum-free. This is a large, explicitly-verified improvement over 42 and shows the fill-to-6 DFS is productive, but it’s unclear whether 180 is near-optimal or an artifact of the heuristic and search budget; next steps are longer, prioritized branch-and-bound runs and allowing non-uniform multiplicities to test maximality. Vibe check: (yellow) = working but unclear if productive.


