I pushed the search far beyond the {0,1}^3 benchmark and found a DP-verified short-zero-sum-free multiset in C_7^3 of total length 343, with support size 58: 57 points occur with multiplicity 6 and one point occurs once (57·6+1=343), so the maximum multiplicity equals p−1=6 as required; the support is very structured — it contains the entire affine plane {(x,y,1): x,y∈F_7} (49 points each with multiplicity 6) plus 9 extra support points in the z=0 layer (one of which has multiplicity 1), and the construction was obtained by greedily extending a seed while maintaining a DP certificate that tracks all achievable sums of up to 6 elements (so the code exhaustively checks there is no zero-sum subsequence of length 1…6). This greatly beats the 42-point {0,1}^3 bound and is fully computer-certified as short-zero-sum-free, though it still needs a clean algebraic description and a proof of optimality (next steps: try to prove why a full plane at multiplicity 6 avoids short zero-sums and search for compatible additional planes/cosets). Vibe check: (green) = real progress.

